# No Unnecessary Effects

Reference: https://react.dev/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect

`useEffect` is an escape hatch for synchronizing with **external systems** (DOM, network, third-party libs). It is NOT for reacting to props/state changes. Using `setState` inside `useEffect` to "sync" internal state causes cascading re-renders and is flagged by `react-hooks/set-state-in-effect`.

## Rules

1. **Never call `setState` inside `useEffect` to reset state when a prop changes.** Use a `key` on the component instead — React will unmount/remount it with fresh state.
2. **Never derive state from props/state via `useEffect`.** Calculate it during rendering (plain `const` or `useMemo`).
3. **Never trigger side effects in response to user events via `useEffect`.** Put the logic in the event handler directly.

## Common anti-patterns and fixes

### Resetting state when a prop changes

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — setState in useEffect to reset on prop change
function RirDrawer({ open }: { open: boolean }) {
  const [selected, setSelected] = useState(2)
  useEffect(() => {
    if (open) setSelected(2)
  }, [open])
}

// ✅ GOOD — use key in the parent to remount with fresh state
<RirDrawer key={pendingSetIdx} open={pendingSetIdx !== null} />
```

### Deriving values from state

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — redundant state + effect
const [filteredItems, setFilteredItems] = useState([])
useEffect(() => {
  setFilteredItems(items.filter(i => i.active))
}, [items])

// ✅ GOOD — derive during render
const filteredItems = items.filter(i => i.active)

// ✅ GOOD — memoize if expensive
const filteredItems = useMemo(() => items.filter(i => i.active), [items])
```

### Sending data on user action

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — effect reacting to state set by an event handler
const [submitted, setSubmitted] = useState(false)
useEffect(() => {
  if (submitted) sendMessage(message)
}, [submitted, message])

// ✅ GOOD — call directly in the event handler
function handleSubmit() {
  sendMessage(message)
  setShowForm(false)
}
```

### Notifying parent of state change

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — effect to propagate state up
useEffect(() => {
  onChange(isOn)
}, [isOn, onChange])

// ✅ GOOD — call parent callback in the same event handler that changes state
function handleClick() {
  setIsOn(!isOn)
  onChange(!isOn)
}
```

## When useEffect IS appropriate

- Subscribing to external stores (`useSyncExternalStore` is even better)
- Fetching data when the component is displayed (TanStack Query / framework primitives are better)
- Synchronizing with non-React DOM (e.g. imperative map widget, analytics on mount)
- Setting up/tearing down event listeners on `window` or `document`
